      average: '<strong>Average the scores:</strong> This obscures important information. A student who excels in content but struggles with organisation needs targeted feedback on organisation — averaging hides this distinction.',
      separate: '<strong>Score each criterion separately:</strong> Correct. Analytic rubrics score each criterion independently, providing transparent, specific feedback that guides improvement in each area.',
      overall: '<strong>Overall impression:</strong> Impressionistic scoring lacks transparency and consistency. Students cannot identify what to improve, and markers may be influenced by the halo effect.'
    },
    r4: {
      calibration: '<strong>Calibration training:</strong> Excellent first step. Having students apply the rubric to sample work and comparing their scores builds shared understanding of standards before they assess peers.',
      structure: '<strong>Structured rubrics:</strong> Essential foundation. Specific criteria with clear descriptors at each level reduce subjectivity and make it harder to give vague positive feedback.',
      examples: '<strong>Show exemplars:</strong> Highly effective. Seeing examples of high-quality and lower-quality feedback — and discussing why — gives students a concrete model to emulate.'
    },
